<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
<p>In 1956, a group of citizens concerned about alcohol-related problems organized the Washtenaw Committee on Alcoholism (WCA), Incorporated as the Washtenaw County Council on Alcoholism in 1960, the Council was renamed several times, eventually gaining its present name in 1972.</p>

<p>Originally offering limited informational and referral services to the public through a voluntary staff, the WCA was recognized in 1976 as having one of the most comprehensive alcoholic treatment programs in the United States. Included in the Council's programs are the Substance Abuse Program offered to junior high school classes, Family Group Therapy Program, workshops, seminars and in-service training.</p>

</bioghist>



<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
<p>The Washtenaw Council on Alcoholism records consist of reports, minutes, newsletters, printed materials, correspondence, and slides dating from 1966 to 1988. The files are arranged alphabetically by topic and chronologically within each folder. The History file provides useful background information about the organization. Also included are various reports and minutes that record the concerns and plans of the organization. The "Slides" folders contain visual images pertaining to the programs the WCA offers to the public.</p>
</scopecontent>

